WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.240
 So we're gonna wrap up this section

00:00:02.240 --> 00:00:05.680
 talking a little bit more about what we would do

00:00:05.680 --> 00:00:07.400
 in order to get the instructions,

00:00:07.400 --> 00:00:09.320
 the machine language instructions,

00:00:09.320 --> 00:00:10.940
 instead of coming from a little switch

00:00:10.940 --> 00:00:14.580
 which is completely fake, but instead coming from the memory.

00:00:14.580 --> 00:00:17.340
 And so to do that, we look a little bit more

00:00:17.340 --> 00:00:19.960
 into computer architecture.

00:00:19.960 --> 00:00:22.520
 We talked before about the ALU,

00:00:22.520 --> 00:00:25.960
 the arithmetic and logic unit, as well as the registers.

00:00:25.960 --> 00:00:28.280
 So the ALU has like an adder in it,

00:00:28.280 --> 00:00:32.680
 maybe a multiplier or a comparison module, all in hardware.

00:00:32.680 --> 00:00:34.960
 Then we have registers which have, you know,

00:00:34.960 --> 00:00:38.960
 bits in them like numbers and their temporary storage.

00:00:38.960 --> 00:00:41.160
 And in addition, we're gonna talk a little more now

00:00:41.160 --> 00:00:42.200
 about the logic.

00:00:42.200 --> 00:00:45.120
 Now the load and store, the way we're gonna do it

00:00:45.120 --> 00:00:48.480
 goes to and from registers for like data memory.

00:00:48.480 --> 00:00:51.320
 But for program memory, there's a couple of things

00:00:51.320 --> 00:00:55.360
 that the CPU uses to control program memory.

00:00:55.360 --> 00:00:59.480
 So one is the PC or program counter register.

00:00:59.480 --> 00:01:04.040
 So this is a register that points to the next instruction

00:01:04.040 --> 00:01:05.760
 we're supposed to execute.

00:01:05.760 --> 00:01:10.280
 So the CPU, when it's ready to execute an instruction,

00:01:10.280 --> 00:01:12.260
 it says, oh, the PC tells me where to load it.

00:01:12.260 --> 00:01:14.920
 So I'm gonna load that instruction from the memory

00:01:14.920 --> 00:01:18.120
 into CIR, current instruction register.

00:01:18.120 --> 00:01:21.040
 And that's just some bits, zeros and one.

00:01:21.040 --> 00:01:23.760
 And then I mentioned the idea of a decoder.

00:01:23.760 --> 00:01:26.100
 And in the previous example, we had some AND gates

00:01:26.100 --> 00:01:28.360
 that were in a sense our decoder.

00:01:28.360 --> 00:01:30.840
 So when you have a real CPU,

00:01:30.840 --> 00:01:32.760
 it has a lot more than two instructions.

00:01:32.760 --> 00:01:35.960
 And the decoder is looking at the pattern of bits

00:01:35.960 --> 00:01:38.440
 in the instruction, decoding it,

00:01:38.440 --> 00:01:42.840
 and then sending logic to the ALU and the registers

00:01:42.840 --> 00:01:46.200
 to activate the right thing to get the right thing to happen.

00:01:46.200 --> 00:01:48.500
 So maybe we're gonna add two registers together

00:01:48.500 --> 00:01:52.240
 and store the result in a different register, okay?

00:01:52.240 --> 00:01:54.760
 And the decoder sees that instruction

00:01:54.760 --> 00:01:57.800
 that is the add two registers

00:01:57.800 --> 00:01:59.760
 and store in another register instruction.

00:01:59.760 --> 00:02:02.800
 And then the decoder sees the pattern of that,

00:02:02.800 --> 00:02:05.240
 and then it activates the right registers,

00:02:05.240 --> 00:02:07.040
 the right arithmetic logic unit,

00:02:07.040 --> 00:02:09.380
 and then causes the instruction to happen

00:02:09.380 --> 00:02:12.280
 in one or a couple of clock cycles,

00:02:12.280 --> 00:02:14.640
 depending on how difficult it is.

00:02:14.640 --> 00:02:17.740
 In the previous example, we had like a zero to reset

00:02:17.740 --> 00:02:20.120
 and a one to add one every clock cycle.

00:02:20.120 --> 00:02:23.600
 So it incremented or it stopped, it went back to zero.

00:02:23.600 --> 00:02:25.400
 But in reality, you need a series

00:02:25.400 --> 00:02:27.940
 of machine language instructions,

00:02:27.940 --> 00:02:31.800
 like set register four to zero,

00:02:31.800 --> 00:02:35.120
 compare register four to zero,

00:02:35.120 --> 00:02:38.440
 increment register four, decrement register four.

00:02:38.440 --> 00:02:40.460
 And so there are binary patterns,

00:02:40.460 --> 00:02:43.780
 which are part of the documentation of a microprocessor.

00:02:43.780 --> 00:02:48.780
 So if the decode unit looks at 0100 for the instruction,

00:02:49.200 --> 00:02:50.840
 it says, oh, that's a zero instruction.

00:02:50.840 --> 00:02:53.960
 And then RRR is three bits for a register

00:02:53.960 --> 00:02:54.960
 from zero through seven.

00:02:54.960 --> 00:02:57.900
 So you're setting register three to zero.

00:02:57.900 --> 00:03:02.260
 And so these are just simple patterns,

00:03:02.260 --> 00:03:04.280
 and they might seem really complex to you,

00:03:04.280 --> 00:03:07.320
 but in some ways, they're actually really easy.

00:03:07.320 --> 00:03:08.480
 The number of things you can do

00:03:08.480 --> 00:03:12.440
 in this machine language is really limited.

00:03:12.440 --> 00:03:16.560
 Now it makes programs a lot more verbose.

00:03:16.560 --> 00:03:19.480
 And usually we don't even write the zeros and ones,

00:03:19.480 --> 00:03:20.920
 we write this stuff called assembly,

00:03:20.920 --> 00:03:22.800
 which we'll talk about coming up.

00:03:22.800 --> 00:03:25.160
 Or we write C, which is a higher level language

00:03:25.160 --> 00:03:26.640
 that then generates assembly,

00:03:26.640 --> 00:03:28.400
 which generates machine language.

00:03:28.400 --> 00:03:30.000
 Or we take a language like Python,

00:03:30.000 --> 00:03:32.840
 which sort of almost completely separates us

00:03:32.840 --> 00:03:34.000
 from the machine language.

00:03:34.000 --> 00:03:36.360
 But then Python itself is written in machine language

00:03:36.360 --> 00:03:38.120
 so that it's really fast.

00:03:38.120 --> 00:03:40.560
 So coming up next, we're going to design

00:03:40.560 --> 00:03:43.080
 a very simple central processing unit.

00:03:43.080 --> 00:03:48.080
 I call it the CDC 8512, inspired by my first computer,

00:03:48.080 --> 00:03:51.680
 the Controlled Data Corporation, CDC 6500.

00:03:51.680 --> 00:03:53.500
 It'll have a complete architecture.

00:03:53.500 --> 00:03:54.920
 It'll be completely defined.

00:03:54.920 --> 00:03:56.200
 It'll have a program counter.

00:03:56.200 --> 00:03:58.080
 It'll have an instruction register.

00:03:58.080 --> 00:04:01.260
 And we will write real, very small programs

00:04:01.260 --> 00:04:04.640
 in CDC 8512 machine code,

00:04:04.640 --> 00:04:07.440
 and then run them on an emulator.

00:04:07.440 --> 00:04:10.020
 (upbeat music)

00:04:13.080 --> 00:04:15.660
 (upbeat music)

